|{{flag|Australia}}
|{{sort|01-01-1901|1 January 1902}}
|{{sort|09-10-1942|[[Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942|9 October 1942]]}} (effective from 1939)
|{{sort|03-03-1986|3 March 1986}} 
|[[Australia Act 1986]]
|
|-
|{{flag|Canada}}
|{{sort|01-07-1867|1 July 1867}}
|{{sort|11-12-1931|11 December 1931}}
|{{sort|17-04-1982|17 April 1982}}
|[[Canada Act 1982]]
|
|-
|{{flag|Ireland}}
|{{sort|06-12-1922|[[Constitution of the Irish Free State|6 December 1922]]}}
|{{sort|11-12-1931|11 December 1931}}
|18 April 1949
|[[Republic of Ireland Act 1948|Republic of Ireland Act]] and [[Ireland Act 1949]]
| The 1916 [[Proclamation of the Irish Republic]] and 1919 [[Irish Declaration of Independence]] were never recognised by the UK but given symbolic priority by post-1922 Irish leaders. From the [[Irish general election, 1932|1932 Irish election]], [[Irish cabinets since 1919|successive governments]] unilaterally amended the state's status: the Constitution (Removal of Oath) Act on 3 May 1933 implicitly abrogated the 1921 [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]]; the [[Constitution (Amendment No. 27) Act 1936|27th amendment]] and [[Executive Authority (External Relations) Act 1936|External Relations Act]], both on 12 December 1936, attenuated [[Irish head of state from 1936 to 1949|the role of the monarchy]]; the [[Enactment of the Constitution of Ireland|enactment of the Constitution]] on 29 December 1937 established the [[President of Ireland|office of President]]; the [[Republic of Ireland Act 1948|Republic of Ireland Act]] came into force on 18 April 1949 with Ireland formally leaving the [[British Commonwealth]]. Related UK statutes included the [[Éire (Confirmation of Agreements) Act 1938]] and the [[Ireland Act 1949]].
|-

|{{flag|Dominion of Newfoundland|Newfoundland}}
|{{sort|26-09-1907|26 September 1907}}
